>>42289489
If you insist on "balancing" your fantasy anthro species, you can give human beings advantages such as the following:
>Less sensitive hearing allows for the employment of sonic weaponry.
>Human fingers allow for greater dexterity than the anthro equivalents, even if they do develop paws, claws or hooves capable of gripping objects.
>Humans have a superior throwing range compared to other species, useful in a fight.
>Human feet are better equipped for bipedal movement, digitigrade and unguligrade species may struggle to keep themselves planted on the ground.
Here's the obvious answer.
Individual human beings in real life aren't balanced against each other, so why would different sapient species need to be? The world isn't a video game.

Anonymous Mon 11 Oct 2021 00:44:00 No.42290505 Report
Quoted By:
>>42290022
There could be other factors that prevent such a roflstomping even if humans were the most underpowered species in a setting.
Do anthros exist in the world when that stuff is directly relevant? If they only appear in modern times, combat prowess matters significantly less than it would in a tribal culture. As tech improves, that gap will continue to shrink, or possibly even invert.
Perhaps that dexterity makes humans excellent tool makers, and anthros make peace/ trade with human tribes in order to obtain higher quality goods.
Maybe the other tribes don't really see humans as a threat, only employing occasional raids while focusing defenses against more dangerous opponents.
Maybe cultural factors come into play.

I think what he's trying to say is that anthros would have the same level of intelect and capacity for technological development as humans, as well as abilities that would far outstrip them in the environment they're accustomed to. A pack of inteligent wolf people would completely BTFO a pack of humans in the alaskan wilderness. While 21st century tech would lessen the gap significantly, humans in their current state would not have advanced to where we are now if anthros had evolved alongside them, because they share the human's capacity for toolmaking and organization while also gaining plenty of advantages from their more feral ancestors, like winter coats and a better sense of hearing/smell, mainly because most writers portray anthros as essentially humans with better senses and other abilities without any real drawbacks.
